hands_on_practices.problem:
The Anger function $\mathbf{J}_{
u}(z)$ and the Weber function $\mathbf{E}_{
u}(z)$ are defined by the integral representations:
$$ \mathbf{J}_{
u}(z) =  rac{1}{\pi} \int_0^\pi \cos(
u	heta - z\sin	heta) \, d	heta $$
$$ \mathbf{E}_{
u}(z) =  rac{1}{\pi} \int_0^\pi \sin(
u	heta - z\sin	heta) \, d	heta $$
These functions are closely related to Bessel functions and arise as particular solutions to the inhomogeneous Bessel differential equation. They possess reflection formulas that connect their values at negative arguments to those at positive arguments. These formulas are given by:
$$ \mathbf{J}_{
u}(-z) = \cos(\pi
u) \mathbf{J}_{
u}(z) - \sin(\pi
u) \mathbf{E}_{
u}(z) $$
$$ \mathbf{E}_{
u}(-z) = \sin(\pi
u) \mathbf{J}_{
u}(z) + \cos(\pi
u) \mathbf{E}_{
u}(z) $$

Given the order $
u = 1/4$ and a specific argument $z_0 > 0$, suppose the values of the Anger and Weber functions are known to be $\mathbf{J}_{1/4}(z_0) = A$ and $\mathbf{E}_{1/4}(z_0) = B$.

Using the reflection formulas provided, determine the value of the Weber function $\mathbf{E}_{1/4}(-z_0)$ in terms of the constants $A$ and $B$.
